# I changed
MODERN BUILD NOTES (CMake)
=========================

This repository vendors the MC-Core ("mccore") library for use by MC-Annotate.
The original upstream documentation predates the CMake-based build found in
this tree.

Requirements:
  - A C++ compiler (GCC/Clang)
  - CMake
  - zlib development headers (e.g. zlib1g-dev on Debian/Ubuntu, zlib-devel on CentOS/RHEL)

Important:
  - Use C++14 (or older). C++17+ is not supported by this codebase as-is.

Example build/install (Linux):
  cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release \
    -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX=/opt/mctools \
    -DCMAKE_CXX_STANDARD=14 -DCMAKE_CXX_EXTENSIONS=ON
  cmake --build build -j
  cmake --install build

Install layout:
  - Headers: <prefix>/include/mccore/...
  - Library: <prefix>/lib/libmccore.so or <prefix>/lib64/libmccore.so (depending on the build)


DEPLOYMENT / RELOCATION (Linux)
===============================

If you need to run on an older distribution (e.g. CentOS 8), prefer building
on that distribution (or inside a CentOS 8 container/VM). Copying binaries
built on a newer distro can fail due to glibc version requirements.

To bundle into a single directory prefix (example: /opt/mctools):

  1) Build + install into a staging directory:
       DESTDIR=$PWD/_pkg cmake --install build

  2) Create a tarball:
       tar -C _pkg -czf mccore-linux-x86_64.tar.gz opt/mctools

  3) On the target machine, extract:
       sudo tar -C / -xzf mccore-linux-x86_64.tar.gz

  4) Ensure the dynamic linker can find the library (choose one):
       export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/opt/mctools/lib64:/opt/mctools/lib:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH
     or
       echo /opt/mctools/lib64 | sudo tee /etc/ld.so.conf.d/mctools.conf
       echo /opt/mctools/lib   | sudo tee -a /etc/ld.so.conf.d/mctools.conf
       sudo ldconfig


PORTABILITY PATCHES
===================

This codebase is historically old; some minimal source changes may be required
to build with modern compilers/standard libraries (e.g. name lookup conflicts
with system calls and stricter STL requirements). These changes are intended to
preserve behavior while improving build compatibility.















